Feb 25, 2019 | 10:22 AM EST DOUG KASS Reducing the Size of Two Investments * As reward to the upside v. downside risk has changed after meaningful price gains in the last 2-3 months I have reduced from very large to medium-sized two of my favorite long investments -

Goldman Sachs and Facebook. $FB was purchased and placed on my Best Ideas List at $137.59 in late November at $137.59 (it's now $164). $GS was bought and put on my Best Ideas List in mid-December at $169.95 (it's now at $201).

@realmoney Reduced two of my favorite (and contrarian longs) - $FB and $GS - on the morning gap. Moved from very large sized to medium sized in these names after the meaningful share price rises since early December. Changing upside v downside. @jimcramer @tomkeene @TeamCavuto
@revshark and I write on @realmoney with him. I respect him immensely in several ways.
Sorry I can no longer debate you Rev as you mischaracterize what I wrote. I didnt say charts are misleading - I wrote that charts are now less RELIABLE.
Do you not think that Warren Buffett provides good advice to long term investors in his letters to shareholders, interviews, etc.?
Then why did you tweet that I said charts no longer work?

As a matter of course I encourage thoughtful and constructive criticism that rigorously addresses my beliefs and analysis. It makes me a better investor by rethinking my views. @realmoney @RevShark Criticism of things you think I am writing/saying (but am not) ... not so much.

I never ever wrote that technical analysis no longer works. I wrote that the reliability of charts/technical analysis have been impaired by changing market structure. Respectfully, Rev, you have to read more carefully before you criticize.

You failed to clearly read my message - and missed the ramifications realmoney.thestreet.com/inve… What I wrote is that market structure changes have likely (somewhat) reduced the reliability of charts.

@realmoney Some Thoughts On Warren Buffett's Letter to Berkshire Shareholders * Strong operating results seen, adjusted for the accounting (and loss) from marketable securities * More flaws became apparent in the company's investing portfolio -

as moats in several large positions have been damaged (most notably Kraft Heinz) * As I did when I appeared at the company's Annual Meeting, I continue to (respectfully) question the investment process at Berkshire (that has, in certain high profile instances, failed to identify

the loss of pricing power in a changing and more competitive business landscape) * 2018 uncovered more evidence that Berkshire Hathaway has become so large that, going forward, it will continue to resemble an S&P Index Fund @jimcramer @tomkeene @TeamCavuto @squawkcnbc
